g.title: Folded Corner.23

g.text: The Prototype pattern, also known as ‘Virtual Copy Constructor’, allows clients to copy an object via the object’s abstraction. A common scenario is that clients should be loosely coupled with their dependencies (i.e. not dependent on their concrete type). This might be because the developer of a 3rd party library prohibits clients from ‘direct’ object instantiation or code requires adaptability ‘ease’ (because it is most likely to change). An additional requirement might be that clients need the ability to copy the dependency. However, copying via an abstraction is often not supported by programming languages (e.g. C++ requires familiarity with the concrete type to use the copy constructor). To comply to both requirements, the Prototype pattern can be used. The Prototype pattern prescribes defining a Prototypical interface containing a ‘Clone’ function. The Prototype interface is implemented by the respective concrete dependency, allowing clients to clone the concrete type via its interface. The Prototype pattern reduces coupling in a system when cloning is required.

g.title: Folded Corner.20
g.desc: The Prototype design pattern compliments the Interface Segreg...

g.text: The Prototype design pattern compliments the Interface Segregation principle by preventing clients from new-ing a particular instance. This enhances the stability of the code. All aspects are compared against an implementation where client is familiar with the concrete type of its dependency to enable copying. This implementation allows direct instantiation. Stability, because the ‘role’ interface of the Prototype prevents clients from direct instantiation of the concrete Prototype, which eliminates unexpected/unwanted situations. This restriction allows to retain more control over the Prototypical instance, which ensures less chance on possible bugs. Less bugs results in a more stable code base. On top of that, the restriction also clarifies design intent.

g.title: Folded Corner.36
g.desc: The Prototype design pattern compliments the Open Closed Prin...

g.text: The Prototype design pattern compliments the Open Closed Principle by allowing object copying without making the client dependent on the concrete type. This enhances the stability, reusability and testability of the code. All aspects are compared against an implementation where client dependents on a concrete object directly to enable copying. Stability, because the client’s dependency (=Prototype) can change without directly affecting client code. As long as the dependency complies to the Prototypical interface, neither the client product nor test code requires change when a new Prototype is introduced. This enables adaptability of the client while preserving stability. Reusability, because client code can be reused with different Prototypes. The reusability is enabled by clients being dependent on a Prototype interface. In contrast, clients being dependent on a concrete dependency (=Prototype) directly, would complicate client reusability and might result in duplication. Testability, because client code is dependent on a Prototype interface, which allows mock-ability. Mock-ability of the client’s dependencies allows the client to be tested in isolation. Isolated tested enables finding issues faster, because the problem window is reduced.

g.title: Folded Corner.57
g.desc: The Prototype pattern provides an alternative to creating obj...

g.text: The Prototype pattern provides an alternative to creating objects from ‘scratch’. This might ‘relief’ clients from difficult or time consuming object instantiations. A Use Case might be that the instantiation of a new object requires a database call. The clients of the object require only a slightly modified version of that object and would make the database call redundant. The Prototype pattern proposes to ‘clone’ the object instead of ‘new-ing’ it. This prevents clients from waiting on ‘expensive’ object creations and allows the clone to be ‘shaped’ to fit the need. Another use case might be that instantiating a new object might be difficult. Difficult, because of the required dependencies that need ‘consultancy’ to create the respective object or because replicating an existing object requires more code and computation (e.g. bring object x, from scratch, into the same state as object y). The Prototype pattern propose to instantiate the object once from scratch and simplify instantiation via cloning throughout the rest of our system. Clients can clone and shape the object, which makes it look-like a new object was created. A prototype manager might be helpful to centralize the available, already created objects. This provides sharing of the prototype instances and allows a plane, default prototype to be saved. This default prototype ‘forms’ the base of every clone.

g.title: Folded Corner.64
g.desc: The Prototype pattern might help in reducing the amount of cl...

g.text: The Prototype pattern might help in reducing the amount of classes in a software system. A problem that might arise is that new classes are defined for relatively small changes. An extensive amount of classes might complicate the code base, due to a decrease in navigability. On top of that the approach, to define classes statically, might not be flexibility enough, because clients would like to have slightly different objects/classes based on runtime conditions. The prototype pattern can be used to reduce the amount of classes to gain flexibility and navigability. A class can be prototyped, shaped and stored in a Prototype Manager. The Prototype manager provides an object template that can be used as a base for other clients. An example, the Prototype pattern might be used as an alternative for the Factory Method pattern to reduce the amount of classes. The Factory Method pattern enforces clients to sub-class both Creator and Product to customize the dependencies of, for example, a Framework. The Prototype pattern prescribes Products to only inherit from a Prototypical interface. The Product (=Prototype) is instantiated on client side and injected into the Framework. The Framework is able to Clone the Product via the injected Prototype. This means the Creator hierarchy, applicable in the Factory Method pattern, parallel to the Product hierarchy, is not required anymore. As a result, the amount of class are reduces and the dependency flexibility is retained. A counter argument, to this example, might be that applying subclassing, only to vary the Dependency a class works with, seems overdone. Another argument might be that the Clone method could be substituted for a Create method. This means the Product is able to create itself from scratch, leaving the Creator hierarchy redundant as well. These arguments are all correct, however the Prototype pattern is a possible solution to class/subclass reduction. In this case the design choice must be made on different arguments as well.

g.title: Folded Corner.69
g.desc: The Prototype design pattern entails both the negative and po...

g.text: The Prototype design pattern entails both the negative and positive side of the Open Closed Principle. The Prototype pattern prescribes an abstraction between concrete Prototype and clients. This enables dependency flexibility resulting in stability of the code base. However, the abstraction also adds an additional form of indirection. This indirection has negative effect on the navigability and debuggability of the code. The applicability of the Prototype design pattern should be considered with care. The Prototype design pattern should be avoided in case no dependency flexibility or client restriction are required. In such a case it might be preferable to use the copy behavior of the concrete type directly.
